natural problem: Compute $\arcsin \left( -\frac{1}{2} \right).$  Express your answer in radians.

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes x :: real
assumes h0 : "x = arcsin (-1/2)"
shows  "x = -pi/6"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Compute $\arcsin \left( -\frac{1}{2} \right).$  Express your answer in radians. The final Answer is -\frac{\pi}{6}
 ### Proof
 Since $\sin \left( -\frac{\pi}{6} \right) = -\frac{1}{2},$ $\arcsin \left( -\frac{1}{2} \right) = \boxed{-\frac{\pi}{6}}.$
 *)

theorem
fixes x :: real
assumes h0 : "x = arcsin (-1/2)"
shows  "x = -pi/6"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
